00:00:20.947 --> 00:00:23.280
SEBASTIAN DETERDING: It's a
best selling techno thriller

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:27.040
turned into a movie, which
is about a demo, a semi

00:00:27.040 --> 00:00:30.240
autonomous program
gaining full autonomy

00:00:30.240 --> 00:00:35.990
and using levelling systems
from an MMORPG to basically turn

00:00:35.990 --> 00:00:39.645
humans into a second speaker
society controlled by computers

00:00:39.645 --> 00:00:42.620
instead of the other way around.

00:00:42.620 --> 00:00:45.090
And connected to that
theory is definitely led

00:00:45.090 --> 00:00:48.360
by the rise of the term or
the concept gamification,

00:00:48.360 --> 00:00:52.310
somewhere around 2010 or 2011,
if you follow Google search

00:00:52.310 --> 00:00:53.610
interests.

00:00:53.610 --> 00:00:56.920
The idea that you could use
elements from games or game

00:00:56.920 --> 00:01:00.720
design as a kind of monosodium
glutamate or crunchy

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:03.551
flakes to edit some other stuff
to make some other stuff more

00:01:03.551 --> 00:01:05.239
palatable.

00:01:05.239 --> 00:01:07.445
And if there is one
thing true to this term

00:01:07.445 --> 00:01:11.355
is that it has the heated
debate from the get go.

00:01:11.355 --> 00:01:14.330
On the one hand, you have
people like the ones who read,

00:01:14.330 --> 00:01:16.230
Gabe Zicherman, he says's
it's the best tools

00:01:16.230 --> 00:01:18.229
humanity has ever invented
to create and sustain

00:01:18.229 --> 00:01:20.700
engagement in people game.

00:01:20.700 --> 00:01:24.030
On the other hand, you have
people like Ian Bogus for those

00:01:24.030 --> 00:01:26.720
choice words
[LAUGHTER] [INAUDIBLE],

00:01:26.720 --> 00:01:28.350
which of course is
a technical term,

00:01:28.350 --> 00:01:30.780
it's a technical term in
philosophy by Harry G.

00:01:30.780 --> 00:01:33.690
Frankfurt, describing people
who just don't care whether what

00:01:33.690 --> 00:01:36.440
they say is true or untrue.

00:01:36.440 --> 00:01:39.550
So when me and my colleague
Stephen [INAUDIBLE] we're

00:01:39.550 --> 00:01:42.520
looking at the debate
around 2011-2012,

00:01:42.520 --> 00:01:45.440
we couldn't help noticing
a couple of things.

00:01:45.440 --> 00:01:49.000
First thing we noticed
is-- as I said,

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:50.400
this is a really heated debate.

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:52.039
This is so heated
that this is not just

00:01:52.039 --> 00:01:53.580
the difference of
opinion, there must

00:01:53.580 --> 00:01:55.750
be something deeper
underlying here

00:01:55.750 --> 00:01:57.450
than just difference of opinion.

00:01:57.450 --> 00:02:00.410
And second, while evangelizers
were evangelizing,

00:02:00.410 --> 00:02:05.030
and critiques were
chastising, very few people

00:02:05.030 --> 00:02:08.539
asked, well, what does the
gamification even mean?

00:02:08.539 --> 00:02:11.170
What are the larger
consequences, the larger

00:02:11.170 --> 00:02:15.980
ramifications of this for us as
individuals living in a society

00:02:15.980 --> 00:02:18.750
where these kind of systems
become more prevelant,

00:02:18.750 --> 00:02:21.870
or for us as a society?

00:02:21.870 --> 00:02:24.920
That's kind of the origin story
of how this book came about.

00:02:24.920 --> 00:02:26.630
In this book, most
of what I'm talking

00:02:26.630 --> 00:02:28.700
about in the first chaper,
the history chapter,

00:02:28.700 --> 00:02:30.849
is basically what I'm
talking about here so.

00:02:30.849 --> 00:02:32.890
While we were digging a
bit deeper in this thing,

00:02:32.890 --> 00:02:35.130
saying why this
heated discourse?

00:02:35.130 --> 00:02:37.150
Why are people so angry?

00:02:37.150 --> 00:02:40.110
We found that gamification--
the gamification discourse--

00:02:40.110 --> 00:02:43.210
is very much in the same
state that the discourse

00:02:43.210 --> 00:02:46.463
around playing was in
the late 1990s, when

00:02:46.463 --> 00:02:50.960
the late Bryan Smith [INAUDIBLE]
game [INAUDIBLE] play.

00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:54.750
Show of hands, anybody
know the ambiguitive play?

00:02:54.750 --> 00:02:55.250
OK.

00:02:55.250 --> 00:02:57.850
Show of hands who's involved
in some form of game studies

00:02:57.850 --> 00:03:00.540
or game research program?

00:03:00.540 --> 00:03:03.280
Yeah, that mapping
sort of makes sense,

00:03:03.280 --> 00:03:06.115
if you're into game research,
you should at a certain point

00:03:06.115 --> 00:03:07.540
come across this book.

00:03:07.540 --> 00:03:10.890
What Sutton Smith and this book
basically makes the argument

00:03:10.890 --> 00:03:14.840
and then shows is that he says
the reason why there hasn't

00:03:14.840 --> 00:03:17.140
been a lot of agreement
about what players

00:03:17.140 --> 00:03:20.160
and what we should
do with the play is

00:03:20.160 --> 00:03:22.580
that the different disciplines
of different rhetorics,

00:03:22.580 --> 00:03:25.570
different ways of framing
the play that are grounded

00:03:25.570 --> 00:03:28.880
in different deeper cultural
rhetorics about what plays

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:31.706
should be and how
plays should function.

00:03:31.706 --> 00:03:34.170
As it says, rhetorics
of plays [INAUDIBLE]

00:03:34.170 --> 00:03:36.610
placed within broader
value systems.

00:03:36.610 --> 00:03:39.559
The popular rhetorics in the
listed settings, the ambiguity

00:03:39.559 --> 00:03:41.600
is that there would be
seven different rhetorics,

00:03:41.600 --> 00:03:43.640
and nobody can
ever agree on one.

00:03:43.640 --> 00:03:47.190
There are these different, large
scale cultural ways of thought

00:03:47.190 --> 00:03:49.660
in which we, more or
less, all participate.

00:03:49.660 --> 00:03:51.785
And that's the reason
why that debate never

00:03:51.785 --> 00:03:54.210
really comes really close.

00:03:54.210 --> 00:03:55.596
And in the same
way, when we look

00:03:55.596 --> 00:03:57.470
at the gamification
[INAUDIBLE] and say yeah,

00:03:57.470 --> 00:03:59.780
that really captures pretty
well the happening here.

00:03:59.780 --> 00:04:02.210
There is a disagreement
here about what

00:04:02.210 --> 00:04:04.050
the proper plays
of plain society

00:04:04.050 --> 00:04:08.165
should be to begin with
about should playing games be

00:04:08.165 --> 00:04:10.960
used to begin before
anything else or not?

00:04:10.960 --> 00:04:12.526
And if so, how
should they be used?

00:04:12.526 --> 00:04:15.818
By whom should they be used, and
for what should they be used?

00:04:15.818 --> 00:04:17.234
Because the thing
that we observe,

00:04:17.234 --> 00:04:19.915
the series games of
gaminification with playful

00:04:19.915 --> 00:04:22.320
designs-- all these
different terms,

00:04:22.320 --> 00:04:24.790
it's basically a kind
of dual cultural moment.

00:04:24.790 --> 00:04:31.630
On the one hand, games in play
leave the traditional spaces

00:04:31.630 --> 00:04:34.850
that they've been confined
in within our modern Western

00:04:34.850 --> 00:04:36.020
nation states and cultures.

00:04:36.020 --> 00:04:38.186
This was the leisure time
of things you did together

00:04:38.186 --> 00:04:40.430
with your friends
in the evening,

00:04:40.430 --> 00:04:42.490
and there were certain
kinds of games.

00:04:42.490 --> 00:04:44.551
And suddenly, there were
also games for learning.

00:04:44.551 --> 00:04:46.175
Suddenly, there was
games for politics.

00:04:46.175 --> 00:04:48.970
And suddenly, everybody plays.

00:04:48.970 --> 00:04:53.500
And then part of that, what
you get as a response to that

00:04:53.500 --> 00:04:55.810
is that just games
become more and more

00:04:55.810 --> 00:04:59.450
pervasive in everyday life,
which we call dilutification

00:04:59.450 --> 00:05:00.830
of culture.

00:05:00.830 --> 00:05:03.140
You see that other
social actors become

00:05:03.140 --> 00:05:07.130
interested in using
games and in impressing

00:05:07.130 --> 00:05:10.895
norms, and regulations,
and values onto games.

00:05:10.895 --> 00:05:13.270
So suddenly, you have a big
debate where people say well,

00:05:13.270 --> 00:05:14.670
games should be gender
aware, and games

00:05:14.670 --> 00:05:16.170
should be more
diverse, because look

00:05:16.170 --> 00:05:19.490
at what turbo misogynistic
space this is.

00:05:19.490 --> 00:05:23.480
And then you have the
existing male game cultures

00:05:23.480 --> 00:05:25.580
revolting against that,
as this result that game

00:05:25.580 --> 00:05:27.380
play becomes more pervasive.

00:05:27.380 --> 00:05:30.580
Suddenly, you have a
cultural discourse.

00:05:30.580 --> 00:05:33.410
Leave out for all the terrible,
terrible online harassment

00:05:33.410 --> 00:05:34.555
of gamer [INAUDIBLE].

00:05:34.555 --> 00:05:38.030
But underneath that is this
underlying cultural discourse,

00:05:38.030 --> 00:05:39.710
who should be allowed
to play games?

00:05:39.710 --> 00:05:41.090
Who should games be for?

00:05:41.090 --> 00:05:44.260
Who should be able to
make these decisions?

00:05:44.260 --> 00:05:47.450
So if Ian Bogost says
something-- gamification

00:05:47.450 --> 00:05:49.950
is marketing bullshit
as a means to capture

00:05:49.950 --> 00:05:52.790
the wild, coveted beast
that is video games

00:05:52.790 --> 00:05:54.340
and to domesticate it.

00:05:54.340 --> 00:05:56.830
Games are a mysterious,
magical, powerful medium.

00:05:56.830 --> 00:05:59.545
He basically says there's
this nature of games.

00:05:59.545 --> 00:06:00.540
This is how games are.

00:06:00.540 --> 00:06:01.459
They're beasts.

00:06:01.459 --> 00:06:02.250
They're this thing.

00:06:02.250 --> 00:06:05.080
And then suddenly, they try
to tame and domesticate.

00:06:05.080 --> 00:06:07.730
What he's basically
saying is games

00:06:07.730 --> 00:06:09.920
belong to us, the game
designers, and the gamers,

00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:11.145
and the game academics.

00:06:11.145 --> 00:06:14.450
But you marketers, please stay
out of our playing fields.

00:06:14.450 --> 00:06:19.780
This is not you should lose
games, which obviously forgets

00:06:19.780 --> 00:06:24.670
that games have been used
for all kinds of purposes

00:06:24.670 --> 00:06:26.150
for the longest
period in history.

00:06:26.150 --> 00:06:28.137
The art game has
[INAUDIBLE] and fluxes

00:06:28.137 --> 00:06:29.970
where Ian Bogost, with
this game [INAUDIBLE]

00:06:29.970 --> 00:06:32.210
definitely also
belongs to, or be it

00:06:32.210 --> 00:06:34.790
war gaming, which
basically goes back

00:06:34.790 --> 00:06:36.900
to Sun Tzu and The Art
of War, because Sun

00:06:36.900 --> 00:06:39.980
Tzu, The Art of War, partially
was based on the culture where

00:06:39.980 --> 00:06:44.140
samurai were taught strategy
and cunning with good things

00:06:44.140 --> 00:06:45.672
of [INAUDIBLE] as a board game.

00:06:45.672 --> 00:06:47.995
So the idea that you could
use games for other things

00:06:47.995 --> 00:06:50.600
than entertainment is
culturally very old.

00:06:50.600 --> 00:06:53.655
But still, we have suddenly
this new cultural debate

00:06:53.655 --> 00:06:55.855
about how should we
use games in society?

00:06:55.855 --> 00:06:57.740
What should their place be?

00:06:57.740 --> 00:07:00.570
And even deeper underlying
that, what kind of society

00:07:00.570 --> 00:07:04.980
do we want to live in to begin
with, and how do we get there?

00:07:04.980 --> 00:07:09.240
And as we were noticing these
kind of clashes of rhetorics,

00:07:09.240 --> 00:07:13.310
we found two
theoreticians very useful

00:07:13.310 --> 00:07:16.410
in mapping the total debate.

00:07:16.410 --> 00:07:19.830
The first one is this very
unlikely, with Victor Turner,

00:07:19.830 --> 00:07:21.732
of the [INAUDIBLE] to theater.

00:07:21.732 --> 00:07:25.000
And he's an anthropologist,
very famous for his early work

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:26.995
about ritual as a
social phenomenon

00:07:26.995 --> 00:07:29.810
for all of those pictures.

00:07:29.810 --> 00:07:34.881
And he noticed that in
pre-modern cultures that

00:07:34.881 --> 00:07:36.630
was played obviously
that was also played,

00:07:36.630 --> 00:07:42.510
the play was usually very well
coached and functionalized

00:07:42.510 --> 00:07:46.640
in these cultures,
namely in passage rights.

00:07:46.640 --> 00:07:49.350
Passage rights, he says,
were these liminal spaces,

00:07:49.350 --> 00:07:53.470
boundary spaces where
people would temporarily

00:07:53.470 --> 00:07:55.560
leave their existing
space in society,

00:07:55.560 --> 00:07:59.190
and play around, and
act excessively to then

00:07:59.190 --> 00:08:02.320
be reintegrated into
society into their new role,

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:04.595
usually in their passage
between being a child,

00:08:04.595 --> 00:08:06.560
and then being the
responsible adult.

00:08:06.560 --> 00:08:09.090
You still have that kind of
thing in the Amish [INAUDIBLE]

00:08:09.090 --> 00:08:11.550
in certain Amish
communities where

00:08:11.550 --> 00:08:14.112
once you're considered
to be at the age

00:08:14.112 --> 00:08:15.820
where you can become
an adult, basically,

00:08:15.820 --> 00:08:18.280
you get to leave the community,
do all the things you were

00:08:18.280 --> 00:08:21.170
never allowed to do in an
Amish community-- jump around

00:08:21.170 --> 00:08:22.945
is the literal
translation, [GERMAN];

00:08:22.945 --> 00:08:26.050
it's from the Germans-- and then
make the decision whether you

00:08:26.050 --> 00:08:27.110
want to return.

00:08:27.110 --> 00:08:29.841
So you get to play around
very literally, as [INAUDIBLE]

00:08:29.841 --> 00:08:30.845
said, in these places.

00:08:30.845 --> 00:08:33.490
But this is completely
functionalized as a ritual

00:08:33.490 --> 00:08:35.830
to reproduce society.

00:08:35.830 --> 00:08:42.679
And what we noticed is in modern
societies, singular societies,

00:08:42.679 --> 00:08:44.465
these liminal
spaces disappeared.

00:08:44.465 --> 00:08:46.480
We don't have a lot
of them, because we're

00:08:46.480 --> 00:08:50.030
not a strongly religious
society anymore.

00:08:50.030 --> 00:08:53.200
But there were
societal spaces that

00:08:53.200 --> 00:08:55.570
retain forms and
shapes of that, only

00:08:55.570 --> 00:08:58.430
they're used and functionalized
in different ways.

00:08:58.430 --> 00:09:02.195
And to notify this, to
indicate this distinction,

00:09:02.195 --> 00:09:05.711
he makes a distinction
between liminal and liminoid.

00:09:05.711 --> 00:09:08.735
He says where it's liminal
spaces, like passage rights,

00:09:08.735 --> 00:09:11.718
like the pre-modern, religious,
and collective things that

00:09:11.718 --> 00:09:12.462
are obligatory.

00:09:12.462 --> 00:09:16.595
We have to do them, their
play is instrumentalized.

00:09:16.595 --> 00:09:20.770
It's a means towards the end
of getting you into society.

00:09:20.770 --> 00:09:23.410
It reproduces the
existing social order

00:09:23.410 --> 00:09:24.753
and improves the means.

00:09:24.753 --> 00:09:30.250
It's a means towards producing
society, whereas limioid spaces

00:09:30.250 --> 00:09:34.380
play becomes something that's
not instrumental, but also

00:09:34.380 --> 00:09:36.100
telling, done for its sake.

00:09:36.100 --> 00:09:38.970
Play becomes something where
you can change the order, even

00:09:38.970 --> 00:09:39.870
if temporarily.

00:09:39.870 --> 00:09:43.710
You can upset the
social order, and play

00:09:43.710 --> 00:09:46.090
becomes a space where you
can question the end society

00:09:46.090 --> 00:09:47.220
pursuits.

00:09:47.220 --> 00:09:50.112
Should we get through this,
instead of just reproducing it?

00:09:50.112 --> 00:09:50.612
Yeah?

00:09:50.612 --> 00:09:52.903
AUDIENCE: Well, what did you
say about the [INAUDIBLE]?

00:09:52.903 --> 00:09:53.740
What is that?

00:09:53.740 --> 00:09:55.781
SEBASTIAN DETERDING:
Autotelic is from the Greek.

00:09:55.781 --> 00:09:58.220
Auto, self, and telos is goal.

00:09:58.220 --> 00:10:00.930
And autotelic means
something is its own goal.

00:10:00.930 --> 00:10:02.849
I do it for its own sake.

00:10:02.849 --> 00:10:03.390
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:10:03.390 --> 00:10:04.890
SEBASTIAN DETERDING:
I eat because I

00:10:04.890 --> 00:10:10.600
enjoy eating, not because
something else, as an example.

00:10:10.600 --> 00:10:14.670
So he notices that we
have not these ritual

00:10:14.670 --> 00:10:17.464
spaces like passage
rights so much anymore,

00:10:17.464 --> 00:10:18.880
but we have these
liminoid spaces.

00:10:18.880 --> 00:10:20.560
These are spaces like art.

00:10:20.560 --> 00:10:22.330
He uses bases like
science, where you

00:10:22.330 --> 00:10:23.860
get to toy around with ideas.

00:10:23.860 --> 00:10:26.275
These are spaces like theater.

00:10:26.275 --> 00:10:28.347
These are spaces like play.

00:10:28.347 --> 00:10:29.180
These are time play.

00:10:29.180 --> 00:10:31.555
All these spaces retain
these ritual functions,

00:10:31.555 --> 00:10:34.040
but they're somehow
used differently.

00:10:34.040 --> 00:10:36.280
Give you a very
practical example.

00:10:36.280 --> 00:10:39.150
Art-- religious art
in pre-modern times

00:10:39.150 --> 00:10:42.530
was a liminal space that
just presented and reproduced

00:10:42.530 --> 00:10:44.480
the religious order
as it should be.

00:10:44.480 --> 00:10:47.240
I'm just showing you how it
should be, [INAUDIBLE], and so

00:10:47.240 --> 00:10:50.375
on, whereas modern liminoid
art is allowed to toy

00:10:50.375 --> 00:10:55.040
around with this and use the
imagery literally, play around

00:10:55.040 --> 00:10:57.740
with the imagery of
previous pre-modern art,

00:10:57.740 --> 00:11:00.690
remix it with Coca-Cola presents
the crucification of Christ

00:11:00.690 --> 00:11:02.380
to make critical,
soulful commentary,

00:11:02.380 --> 00:11:05.975
to speak about is this the
kind of commercialized society

00:11:05.975 --> 00:11:09.465
in which we live and should be
living in that kind of society.

00:11:09.465 --> 00:11:12.950
And we found this distinction
between lininal and liminoid

00:11:12.950 --> 00:11:15.420
helped us very well to tease
out the different political

00:11:15.420 --> 00:11:20.140
positions people had
towards communification.

00:11:20.140 --> 00:11:22.098
The second poll that we
found was very useful

00:11:22.098 --> 00:11:24.472
is from another book that most
of the game studies people

00:11:24.472 --> 00:11:27.010
know, that is [INAUDIBLE],
a French philosopher

00:11:27.010 --> 00:11:33.970
in the 1950s, Men Playing
Games, [FRENCH], or [FRENCH]?

00:11:33.970 --> 00:11:34.490
[FRENCH]?

00:11:34.490 --> 00:11:35.960
AUDIENCE: [FRENCH].

00:11:35.960 --> 00:11:39.300
SEBASTIAN DETERDING: Yeah,
where he said that basically,

00:11:39.300 --> 00:11:41.160
all kinds of play and
game forms, that we

00:11:41.160 --> 00:11:45.020
have a culture, a loosely
folding on a spectrum of two

00:11:45.020 --> 00:11:45.860
poles.

00:11:45.860 --> 00:11:51.050
One pole he declares with
the Latin ludus for basically

00:11:51.050 --> 00:11:55.845
a rule based game that's very
orderly, where you strive

00:11:55.845 --> 00:11:59.509
in order to reach goals;
every typical board

00:11:59.509 --> 00:12:01.342
game, or social game,
or video game that you

00:12:01.342 --> 00:12:03.290
can think of on the one hand.

00:12:03.290 --> 00:12:07.690
And on the other hand, you have
this free form improvisational,

00:12:07.690 --> 00:12:10.790
explorational, tumultuous play.

00:12:10.790 --> 00:12:13.940
Think about children playing
pretend play, or Lego.

00:12:13.940 --> 00:12:17.690
So all games and play forms have
basically these two ideal poles

00:12:17.690 --> 00:12:21.340
in them, and things fall
somewhere on these poles.

00:12:21.340 --> 00:12:27.330
And we notice that if we
take these two dimensions

00:12:27.330 --> 00:12:29.110
and look at all the
different rhetorics--

00:12:29.110 --> 00:12:31.060
and we could talk about
the rhetorics later.

00:12:31.060 --> 00:12:32.809
But if we take all the
different rhetorics

00:12:32.809 --> 00:12:38.640
there are, then
they pretty neatly

00:12:38.640 --> 00:12:40.200
form this clear clustering.

00:12:40.200 --> 00:12:42.310
They fall into two
clusters of opinions

00:12:42.310 --> 00:12:45.670
which are these underlying
rhetorical disagreements

00:12:45.670 --> 00:12:49.680
about what games and plays
should be in society.

00:12:49.680 --> 00:12:53.600
On the one hand, you
have people who very much

00:12:53.600 --> 00:12:55.370
like games-- structures.

00:12:55.370 --> 00:12:58.790
There's more structures, more
rules, more feedback systems

00:12:58.790 --> 00:13:01.340
that are very liminal,
but not liminal

00:13:01.340 --> 00:13:03.820
in the traditional,
pre-modern way reproducing

00:13:03.820 --> 00:13:06.260
religious order, but
liminal in a modern way,

00:13:06.260 --> 00:13:09.569
reproducing the existing
social order of society.

00:13:09.569 --> 00:13:12.110
Basically, their position's the
current social order is good.

00:13:12.110 --> 00:13:12.651
It's perfect.

00:13:12.651 --> 00:13:18.270
Society should be as it is, but
it has some flaws in execution,

00:13:18.270 --> 00:13:21.460
and we should use
gains as technologies

00:13:21.460 --> 00:13:23.250
that governments and
organizations can

00:13:23.250 --> 00:13:25.720
use to perfect the execution.

00:13:29.280 --> 00:13:32.060
It's not that the way
organizations or businesses

00:13:32.060 --> 00:13:33.500
organized as broken.

00:13:33.500 --> 00:13:36.150
It's just that people
aren't motivated enough,

00:13:36.150 --> 00:13:38.376
so games are a great tool
to motivate them more.

00:13:38.376 --> 00:13:41.600
I thought maybe we should fix
the organizations themselves,

00:13:41.600 --> 00:13:44.746
whereas the opposite poll, most
people who say gamification's

00:13:44.746 --> 00:13:48.400
bad are the ones
who more or less see

00:13:48.400 --> 00:13:49.790
the current social order as bad.

00:13:49.790 --> 00:13:52.210
They are typically
progressive and critical

00:13:52.210 --> 00:13:55.470
in general in their
political views.

00:13:55.470 --> 00:13:58.340
But say play-- the
practice of play,

00:13:58.340 --> 00:14:02.170
like the [INAUDIBLE] thing is
a great practice for people

00:14:02.170 --> 00:14:04.620
to resist the existing
order and discover together

00:14:04.620 --> 00:14:09.140
what kind of world
we want to begin with

00:14:09.140 --> 00:14:13.047
and to give you just some ideas
of these different rhetorics

00:14:13.047 --> 00:14:14.710
that we find.

00:14:14.710 --> 00:14:20.530
So some of the rhetorics
are, for instance, things

00:14:20.530 --> 00:14:21.710
like well being.

00:14:21.710 --> 00:14:24.720
That's people like
Jane McGonigal,

00:14:24.720 --> 00:14:27.840
people like Miguel [INAUDIBLE],
people like myself that

00:14:27.840 --> 00:14:31.490
speak about self determination
theory, [INAUDIBLE],

00:14:31.490 --> 00:14:32.220
the good life.

00:14:32.220 --> 00:14:34.800
And we all say well,
what's the good life

00:14:34.800 --> 00:14:36.430
that we all aspire to?

00:14:36.430 --> 00:14:38.875
And obviously, in light of
that, our current society's

00:14:38.875 --> 00:14:39.960
pretty broken.

00:14:39.960 --> 00:14:41.340
But here's the thing about play.

00:14:41.340 --> 00:14:43.048
Play is a realized
form of the good life,

00:14:43.048 --> 00:14:50.120
so we all strive to get there,
or things like performance.

00:14:50.120 --> 00:14:52.030
So these are people
who do pervasive games

00:14:52.030 --> 00:14:55.100
or who do LARPs, like
action role playing games;

00:14:55.100 --> 00:14:58.719
all these much, much more free
form play form to say, well,

00:14:58.719 --> 00:15:00.260
these are great
activities for people

00:15:00.260 --> 00:15:02.140
to get together and
experience that they

00:15:02.140 --> 00:15:07.220
can form a community, even if
a temporal community together.

00:15:07.220 --> 00:15:10.390
And on the other hand, you have
rhetorics like reinforcement,

00:15:10.390 --> 00:15:12.780
so people like
[INAUDIBLE] and others

00:15:12.780 --> 00:15:18.309
who raw on behaviorist modes
of thinking or behaviorist

00:15:18.309 --> 00:15:20.100
modes of thinking about
games and say games

00:15:20.100 --> 00:15:23.170
are basically these
incentives doling machines.

00:15:23.170 --> 00:15:25.000
And so therefore,
they're a great way

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:28.660
of reproducing or incentivizing
certain behaviors.

00:15:28.660 --> 00:15:31.790
Or a bit more complex, nudging.

00:15:31.790 --> 00:15:34.340
A lot of people say games
are basically nudges.

00:15:34.340 --> 00:15:36.340
Just a show of hands, who
knows the term nudging

00:15:36.340 --> 00:15:39.480
as a technical term?

00:15:39.480 --> 00:15:40.530
OK.

00:15:40.530 --> 00:15:45.960
So who knows behavioral
economics as a term?

00:15:45.960 --> 00:15:51.470
So neoclassical
economics basically

00:15:51.470 --> 00:15:53.220
says people are rational actors.

00:15:53.220 --> 00:15:54.470
Give me the right information.

00:15:54.470 --> 00:15:55.928
Give me the right
incentives, and I

00:15:55.928 --> 00:15:58.440
will do what you want me to do.

00:15:58.440 --> 00:16:01.730
If I know this is helpful for
me, and I care about my health,

00:16:01.730 --> 00:16:05.802
I'm definitely going
to act healthy.

00:16:05.802 --> 00:16:08.010
Only then, psychology showed
us that is not the case.

00:16:08.010 --> 00:16:09.430
You can give people
as much information,

00:16:09.430 --> 00:16:11.929
and they might care as much as
they want about their health,

00:16:11.929 --> 00:16:14.680
but they still don't behave
healthily necessarily

00:16:14.680 --> 00:16:17.500
which led a lot of
economists saying to us well,

00:16:17.500 --> 00:16:21.275
why then do people
behave unhealthily?

00:16:21.275 --> 00:16:23.150
And they started to run
empirical experiments

00:16:23.150 --> 00:16:25.890
where they say, this is how
economic theory predicts

00:16:25.890 --> 00:16:28.080
how people will
behave, and here's

00:16:28.080 --> 00:16:29.760
how they actually behave.

00:16:29.760 --> 00:16:31.700
So there is a gap
there between the two,

00:16:31.700 --> 00:16:33.612
but this gap is predictable.

00:16:33.612 --> 00:16:34.320
It's a repeating.

00:16:34.320 --> 00:16:37.460
It's a reoccurring pattern.

00:16:37.460 --> 00:16:40.210
One of these reoccurring
patterns, for instance,

00:16:40.210 --> 00:16:43.800
is temporal discounting, which
is just a fancy technical term

00:16:43.800 --> 00:16:46.490
for I care for the thing
right in front of me

00:16:46.490 --> 00:16:51.610
much more than for a
thing way in the future.

00:16:51.610 --> 00:16:54.830
If they did actual economic
disbursement to people saying,

00:16:54.830 --> 00:17:00.293
do you want $1 now or
$100 a month from now?

00:17:00.293 --> 00:17:02.334
A pure rational actor
would always take the $100,

00:17:02.334 --> 00:17:02.834
let's say.

00:17:02.834 --> 00:17:05.903
Because again, in no way,
shape, or form will inflation,

00:17:05.903 --> 00:17:09.970
by that point, have
invalidated the $100 that much.

00:17:09.970 --> 00:17:13.177
But they found the majority
of people took the $1 now.

00:17:13.177 --> 00:17:15.319
And so they enlisted
all these kind

00:17:15.319 --> 00:17:17.750
of cognitive biases
and heuristics,

00:17:17.750 --> 00:17:19.349
these weird ways
in which we deviate

00:17:19.349 --> 00:17:20.980
from actual rational behavior.

00:17:20.980 --> 00:17:23.561
And then they said look at
games, at least that rhetoric.

00:17:23.561 --> 00:17:24.560
They said look at games.

00:17:24.560 --> 00:17:27.190
They're basically
machines for exploiting

00:17:27.190 --> 00:17:30.930
these kind of reliable
flaws in our thinking.

00:17:30.930 --> 00:17:32.670
And so therefore,
games are great for us

00:17:32.670 --> 00:17:34.700
to learn how to exploit
them to get people

00:17:34.700 --> 00:17:36.044
to do other stuff, as well.

00:17:43.770 --> 00:17:45.670
So so much for that.

00:17:45.670 --> 00:17:49.940
I'd like to finish, as I said,
with teasing out scenarios,

00:17:49.940 --> 00:17:52.457
so what are the visions
underlying here then?

00:17:52.457 --> 00:17:54.800
Then we'll get into debating.

00:17:54.800 --> 00:17:58.110
Namely, what are the positive or
negative visions that come out

00:17:58.110 --> 00:18:01.000
of these different rhetorics?

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:04.420
Starting with the positive one,
on both sides that we face,

00:18:04.420 --> 00:18:06.690
you can slice and
dice them as you want.

00:18:06.690 --> 00:18:10.030
I slice and dice them in three
positive scenarios, and lots

00:18:10.030 --> 00:18:13.280
of issues with them that
we can no longer debate.

00:18:13.280 --> 00:18:17.450
The positive vision, the
best possible world version

00:18:17.450 --> 00:18:21.690
of engagement-- the first
one is engagement, which

00:18:21.690 --> 00:18:23.983
is a terrible, over-used term.

00:18:23.983 --> 00:18:32.710
But it's basically the idea that
we can harness all the three

00:18:32.710 --> 00:18:36.420
cycles, all the free
energy, all the cognitive

00:18:36.420 --> 00:18:37.882
surplus', [INAUDIBLE].

00:18:37.882 --> 00:18:40.090
Thanks to the fact that
people are now online, and no

00:18:40.090 --> 00:18:41.951
necessarily always
watching television,

00:18:41.951 --> 00:18:44.075
we can use all the hours
they poured into Wikipedia

00:18:44.075 --> 00:18:47.802
for really productive purposes.

00:18:47.802 --> 00:18:49.260
And then people
like Jane McGonigal

00:18:49.260 --> 00:18:50.510
said well, that's great.

00:18:50.510 --> 00:18:54.169
If we could use games,
you can learn from games.

00:18:54.169 --> 00:18:56.210
And she put in this paper,
because it's basically

00:18:56.210 --> 00:18:58.785
the white paper that
underlies, "Reality is Broken,"

00:18:58.785 --> 00:19:02.550
which she wrote back at the
institute for the future.

00:19:02.550 --> 00:19:05.460
We can use games as engines
for a massively [INAUDIBLE]

00:19:05.460 --> 00:19:09.610
collaboration and participation
to organize and incite people

00:19:09.610 --> 00:19:11.360
towards productive
things like solving

00:19:11.360 --> 00:19:13.376
complex scientific
issues, and science games,

00:19:13.376 --> 00:19:20.970
or stuff like that, or use
games for civic participation,

00:19:20.970 --> 00:19:24.100
or the aspect of games,
like DIY democracy,

00:19:24.100 --> 00:19:28.160
where you would get points
for being an active citizen.

00:19:28.160 --> 00:19:30.230
The one issue-- lots of
issues, but one issue

00:19:30.230 --> 00:19:34.565
I have with that is even if
that would insight engagement

00:19:34.565 --> 00:19:38.215
of people-- for instance,
use this to report pot holes

00:19:38.215 --> 00:19:41.340
in your street, it would
always structure participation

00:19:41.340 --> 00:19:43.000
of people in a certain manner.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:45.425
So if we see this as
a vision of society,

00:19:45.425 --> 00:19:50.844
we have to be aware that every
structure for participation

00:19:50.844 --> 00:19:52.760
creates structures of
who gets to participate,

00:19:52.760 --> 00:19:55.742
who's included in the executing.

00:19:55.742 --> 00:19:57.915
You can also say who
has technological access

00:19:57.915 --> 00:19:58.915
to these kinds of tools?

00:19:58.915 --> 00:20:01.112
Who runs around the whole
time with a smartphone?

00:20:01.112 --> 00:20:02.570
Who even cares about this?

00:20:02.570 --> 00:20:05.041
Who has the technological
literacy to use these tools?

00:20:05.041 --> 00:20:06.790
That is with all the
citizen participation

00:20:06.790 --> 00:20:09.907
tools, who actually uses
this to report pot holes?

00:20:09.907 --> 00:20:12.115
And again, you find that
this is very much stratified

00:20:12.115 --> 00:20:13.750
by socio-economic status.

00:20:16.340 --> 00:20:19.060
The second positive
vision is community.

00:20:19.060 --> 00:20:22.180
That's what I talked about as
performance is the idea that we

00:20:22.180 --> 00:20:25.280
can use games and play
to bring people together

00:20:25.280 --> 00:20:27.740
and to experience hey,
we like each other.

00:20:27.740 --> 00:20:29.100
We're pretty much alike.

00:20:29.100 --> 00:20:32.897
We want the same
things, and we think

00:20:32.897 --> 00:20:35.480
that this thing in our society
is built, and so let's together

00:20:35.480 --> 00:20:36.190
get together and fix it.

00:20:36.190 --> 00:20:37.898
So it's a way of
bringing together people

00:20:37.898 --> 00:20:40.500
into new forms of community.

00:20:40.500 --> 00:20:42.110
This goes back to
early movements,

00:20:42.110 --> 00:20:46.920
like the new games
movement back in the Bay

00:20:46.920 --> 00:20:50.955
Area in the 1970s which
underlies a lot of the still

00:20:50.955 --> 00:20:54.880
Utopian thinking in Silicon
Valley where they basically

00:20:54.880 --> 00:20:57.235
said with the Vietnam
War going, can't we

00:20:57.235 --> 00:21:00.130
create non-competitive games
that get people together

00:21:00.130 --> 00:21:01.950
in order to understand
that that is also

00:21:01.950 --> 00:21:04.425
a form of co-existing instead
of constantly combating

00:21:04.425 --> 00:21:05.610
each other?

00:21:05.610 --> 00:21:07.420
And as Stewart Brand
back then said,

00:21:07.420 --> 00:21:10.580
you can't change a game by
winning it, or losing it,

00:21:10.580 --> 00:21:12.130
or refereeing it,
or spectating it,

00:21:12.130 --> 00:21:13.260
because then you're still
playing by the rules.

00:21:13.260 --> 00:21:15.650
You still have to create
a new game together

00:21:15.650 --> 00:21:18.560
to leave the old
society and to move on.

00:21:18.560 --> 00:21:20.860
And contemporary
examples of that

00:21:20.860 --> 00:21:23.474
are things like you're
guerrilla gardening,

00:21:23.474 --> 00:21:25.390
and there are games
around guerrilla gardening

00:21:25.390 --> 00:21:26.830
as a community.

00:21:26.830 --> 00:21:31.450
Or my favorite example is
Massively Multiplayer Soba

00:21:31.450 --> 00:21:33.312
by tilt factor.

00:21:33.312 --> 00:21:34.770
The treasure hunt
through New York,

00:21:34.770 --> 00:21:37.710
through one of New York's
most diverse neighborhoods.

00:21:37.710 --> 00:21:39.660
And the idea is the
difference teams

00:21:39.660 --> 00:21:42.200
get sheets with
ingredients that they

00:21:42.200 --> 00:21:44.005
have to bring to
the final cookout,

00:21:44.005 --> 00:21:46.220
where people cook together,
only the ingredients are

00:21:46.220 --> 00:21:49.932
written in different languages;
Hebrew, Hindi, whatever.

00:21:49.932 --> 00:21:52.964
So you have to go through
this neighborhood,

00:21:52.964 --> 00:21:54.964
find people to translate
the ingredients to you,

00:21:54.964 --> 00:21:56.800
and then tell you
where you actually find

00:21:56.800 --> 00:21:59.000
all these local ingredients.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:00.983
That way, naturally
getting into conversations

00:22:00.983 --> 00:22:03.399
with people in that neighborhood
you would otherwise never

00:22:03.399 --> 00:22:04.139
have talked to.

00:22:04.139 --> 00:22:05.805
And then the game
gives you extra points

00:22:05.805 --> 00:22:08.332
for bringing stories about
food from that culture

00:22:08.332 --> 00:22:10.290
or bringing actual people
from the neighborhood

00:22:10.290 --> 00:22:11.165
to the final cookout.

00:22:15.640 --> 00:22:17.260
One issue again--
lots of issues,

00:22:17.260 --> 00:22:19.250
but one issue with
that is that I'm always

00:22:19.250 --> 00:22:21.440
wondering to what extent--
these are basically

00:22:21.440 --> 00:22:25.830
again, things hipsters can do
to make themselves feel well

00:22:25.830 --> 00:22:28.440
versus to what extent are
these things that actually cite

00:22:28.440 --> 00:22:33.755
large scale social action or
commodify your [INAUDIBLE],

00:22:33.755 --> 00:22:35.240
you'll find.

00:22:35.240 --> 00:22:39.450
The third positive vision
is hacking; hacking systems.

00:22:39.450 --> 00:22:42.115
The underlying idea there,
and a lot of the references

00:22:42.115 --> 00:22:44.930
will say well, if there's
one thing about games that's

00:22:44.930 --> 00:22:46.620
great it's their systems.

00:22:46.620 --> 00:22:48.380
Or one thing game's
good at is systems,

00:22:48.380 --> 00:22:50.753
and one thing that
you can do with games

00:22:50.753 --> 00:22:54.200
is you learn systems thinking.

00:22:54.200 --> 00:22:57.101
Anybody know September 12?

00:22:57.101 --> 00:23:00.350
One of the early news
games, persuasive games.

00:23:00.350 --> 00:23:03.370
The idea came out right
after September 11th,

00:23:03.370 --> 00:23:05.550
shortly thereafter
by Gonzalo Frasca.

00:23:05.550 --> 00:23:07.880
You basically see
this little landscape

00:23:07.880 --> 00:23:11.390
in some long,
disparate Arab country.

00:23:11.390 --> 00:23:13.590
You see some people
running around

00:23:13.590 --> 00:23:18.620
in quote, unquote,
"terrorist" uniforms,

00:23:18.620 --> 00:23:21.664
and then you just have
this targeting circle.

00:23:21.664 --> 00:23:23.330
And then you can
choose whether you want

00:23:23.330 --> 00:23:25.100
to fire bombs with them or not.

00:23:25.100 --> 00:23:27.860
When you fire bombs,
inevitably you

00:23:27.860 --> 00:23:29.676
will create collateral
damage in terms

00:23:29.676 --> 00:23:30.800
of people and other things.

00:23:30.800 --> 00:23:33.280
And inevitably,
people standing around

00:23:33.280 --> 00:23:36.165
that will mourn for the
dead, and then some of them

00:23:36.165 --> 00:23:38.580
will likewise transform
into terrorists.

00:23:38.580 --> 00:23:42.800
So it's the systemic model
of violence beget violence.

00:23:42.800 --> 00:23:45.262
By attacking, you will only
create more resistance,

00:23:45.262 --> 00:23:46.500
basically.

00:23:46.500 --> 00:23:47.970
You may disagree
with the argument,

00:23:47.970 --> 00:23:49.657
but it's a basic
way of showing you

00:23:49.657 --> 00:23:52.970
how games can model a
system and show a system

00:23:52.970 --> 00:23:54.160
and can [INAUDIBLE] systems.

00:23:54.160 --> 00:23:56.140
So the argument of
hacking, as well;

00:23:56.140 --> 00:23:57.940
games are great for
systems thinking

00:23:57.940 --> 00:24:00.970
or learnings to this
kind of systems thinking.

00:24:00.970 --> 00:24:04.140
And by making games
about the broken systems

00:24:04.140 --> 00:24:07.950
we live in, like in those
airport and security,

00:24:07.950 --> 00:24:11.100
about constantly changing
new rules; what is allowed,

00:24:11.100 --> 00:24:12.304
what is not allowed.

00:24:12.304 --> 00:24:17.880
You notice how broken that
kind of TSA system is,

00:24:17.880 --> 00:24:20.855
and by learning to
build systems ourselves

00:24:20.855 --> 00:24:23.530
through game design and all
kinds of tools that open up

00:24:23.530 --> 00:24:26.470
game design for other
people, we might actually

00:24:26.470 --> 00:24:29.401
educate a generation
of people who can then

00:24:29.401 --> 00:24:31.192
use that game design
and knowledge in order

00:24:31.192 --> 00:24:34.880
to redesign the broken social
systems in which we live.

00:24:34.880 --> 00:24:38.310
The issue with
that is obviously,

00:24:38.310 --> 00:24:40.695
anybody has yet to show me
that there is data for that,

00:24:40.695 --> 00:24:43.380
that that actually happens.

00:24:43.380 --> 00:24:44.160
OK.

00:24:44.160 --> 00:24:47.870
Final three, dystopia.

00:24:47.870 --> 00:24:49.400
The first one is
obviously the one

00:24:49.400 --> 00:24:51.380
that you most likely will come
across the most [INAUDIBLE]

00:24:51.380 --> 00:24:53.213
when people were talking
about gamification.

00:24:53.213 --> 00:24:56.300
That is this is a
perfect control society.

00:24:56.300 --> 00:25:01.116
And my favorite one, has anybody
seen the talk by Jesse Schell?

00:25:01.116 --> 00:25:02.220
The Gamepocalypse.

00:25:02.220 --> 00:25:04.830
That's one of the other
initial pieces of media

00:25:04.830 --> 00:25:06.606
that the whole
gamification thing started.

00:25:06.606 --> 00:25:10.640
It's a talk he gave in 2010
at a game design conference,

00:25:10.640 --> 00:25:13.472
and he described the
future world in which game

00:25:13.472 --> 00:25:15.070
designers would rule.

00:25:15.070 --> 00:25:16.440
And on, and on, and on it goes.

00:25:16.440 --> 00:25:19.610
It's a five minute riff within
the talk where he just runs

00:25:19.610 --> 00:25:22.370
with the idea and says, what
if all kinds of organizations

00:25:22.370 --> 00:25:24.210
and governments
would basically start

00:25:24.210 --> 00:25:25.930
to use point of
incentives systems

00:25:25.930 --> 00:25:29.820
to get people to do
everything they want to do.

00:25:29.820 --> 00:25:31.070
And people say, this is silly.

00:25:31.070 --> 00:25:31.861
This is ridiculous.

00:25:31.861 --> 00:25:32.700
This is also scary.

00:25:32.700 --> 00:25:34.754
The only thing is it's
also becoming a reality.

00:25:34.754 --> 00:25:37.170
Shortly after the talk, there
was this sort of green goose

00:25:37.170 --> 00:25:39.130
which actually did sensor kids.

00:25:39.130 --> 00:25:42.589
So you can use ubiquitous
computing everywhere,

00:25:42.589 --> 00:25:43.880
especially to brush your teeth.

00:25:43.880 --> 00:25:46.030
Some people are obsessed
with brushing their teeth

00:25:46.030 --> 00:25:49.150
and getting points for it-- to
measure everything, and then

00:25:49.150 --> 00:25:50.930
set up your own reward
system for that,

00:25:50.930 --> 00:25:52.831
and you have these
default senses that you

00:25:52.831 --> 00:25:55.450
can use for everything else.

00:25:55.450 --> 00:25:57.760
And if you say well, that's
nice if it's for people.

00:25:57.760 --> 00:26:00.170
That's not what
organizations do-- well,

00:26:00.170 --> 00:26:02.130
this year's one part
of the health program

00:26:02.130 --> 00:26:05.290
that I was introduced to at
Northeastern, which I find very

00:26:05.290 --> 00:26:06.500
cute, which is Virgin Pulse.

00:26:06.500 --> 00:26:09.810
Basically, it's one of these
health trackers, step trackers.

00:26:09.810 --> 00:26:12.890
And if I use the step tracker
for my university, hey.

00:26:12.890 --> 00:26:14.870
I actually get
points, and the points

00:26:14.870 --> 00:26:17.980
are translated into
reduced insurance premiums.

00:26:20.900 --> 00:26:23.420
Now you might say well-- a lot
of my colleagues said well,

00:26:23.420 --> 00:26:24.070
this is great.

00:26:24.070 --> 00:26:26.810
You're getting money, so
why shouldn't I do it?

00:26:26.810 --> 00:26:30.000
I said well, I don't
know if I actually

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:32.820
want either my employer
or my health insurance

00:26:32.820 --> 00:26:35.906
to know how healthy or unhealthy
my behavior [INAUDIBLE] myself.

00:26:35.906 --> 00:26:38.670
And then the next time
I switch an insurance,

00:26:38.670 --> 00:26:42.120
the insurance looks at
the data and says-- hm.

00:26:42.120 --> 00:26:44.760
We should raise your premium.

00:26:44.760 --> 00:26:47.210
The larger issue behind
that is basically

00:26:47.210 --> 00:26:49.740
that most of these
systems are at face value

00:26:49.740 --> 00:26:52.510
are sold as more
fun or rewards or

00:26:52.510 --> 00:26:54.490
empowerment to the individual.

00:26:54.490 --> 00:26:56.310
Like Rescue Time
is this application

00:26:56.310 --> 00:26:57.520
that you can let running.

00:26:57.520 --> 00:26:59.621
And then it tells
you, just by keeping

00:26:59.621 --> 00:27:01.370
in the back end, what
kind of applications

00:27:01.370 --> 00:27:04.760
were running all through
the day and what kind

00:27:04.760 --> 00:27:06.554
of browser windows
you had open in order

00:27:06.554 --> 00:27:08.970
to discover what you're time
syncs are in order to be more

00:27:08.970 --> 00:27:10.396
productive as an individual.

00:27:10.396 --> 00:27:11.150
Yay.

00:27:11.150 --> 00:27:12.700
Only then there's
this nice button,

00:27:12.700 --> 00:27:15.050
Looking for Rescue Time for
Entire Team or Organization,

00:27:15.050 --> 00:27:16.560
click here.

00:27:16.560 --> 00:27:18.220
And then you see the
management feature

00:27:18.220 --> 00:27:19.950
which allows the manager,
who installs this

00:27:19.950 --> 00:27:22.090
all across the team to see
exactly what everybody's

00:27:22.090 --> 00:27:25.830
actually doing on their
computer the whole day.

00:27:25.830 --> 00:27:29.650
And obviously, this
issue is true everywhere

00:27:29.650 --> 00:27:32.950
we use gamified
applications are installed,

00:27:32.950 --> 00:27:35.510
which according to the
vision, will be everywhere.

00:27:35.510 --> 00:27:37.247
So you can even
imagine something

00:27:37.247 --> 00:27:38.810
like Amazon saying
hey, because we

00:27:38.810 --> 00:27:40.490
want people to read
more books, we're

00:27:40.490 --> 00:27:41.675
going to deal out
virtual rewards

00:27:41.675 --> 00:27:43.299
and incentives for
people to read more,

00:27:43.299 --> 00:27:46.510
because then we make more
money only while I do so.

00:27:46.510 --> 00:27:49.178
And then I read all the
volumes of Das Capital,

00:27:49.178 --> 00:27:50.761
somebody else might
also be interested

00:27:50.761 --> 00:27:53.052
in that kind of data, that
I'm actually currently

00:27:53.052 --> 00:27:55.950
interested in Marxism.

00:27:55.950 --> 00:27:59.120
The third issue there is that
face value of fun and self

00:27:59.120 --> 00:28:01.510
realization at companies.

00:28:01.510 --> 00:28:04.870
And all Silicon Valley
companies have to have sleds.

00:28:04.870 --> 00:28:06.280
This here is at YouTube.

00:28:06.280 --> 00:28:08.206
Obviously, a YouTube red.

00:28:08.206 --> 00:28:11.020
I recently did a bit of
research around playful offices.

00:28:11.020 --> 00:28:13.498
They really have all sleds
somehow, for some reason.

00:28:13.498 --> 00:28:14.980
We can talk about that.

00:28:14.980 --> 00:28:19.190
But that, in the back end, is
really covert exploitation.

00:28:19.190 --> 00:28:21.520
We make it so fun and so
comfy here in this place

00:28:21.520 --> 00:28:24.395
that you never want to leave
the workplace, at which point

00:28:24.395 --> 00:28:27.920
then, you get suicides
and exhaustion in places

00:28:27.920 --> 00:28:34.230
like the Las Vegas downtown
project run by Zappos there,

00:28:34.230 --> 00:28:37.150
or as [INAUDIBLE] nicely
put it, gamification

00:28:37.150 --> 00:28:40.760
is a mechanism of
decoupling alienation.

00:28:40.760 --> 00:28:43.310
I feel like I'm not
realizing myself.

00:28:43.310 --> 00:28:45.230
I feel I'm not doing
what I'm passionate

00:28:45.230 --> 00:28:49.770
about from exploitation.

00:28:49.770 --> 00:28:53.120
With gamification, I may not
be alienated by my working,

00:28:53.120 --> 00:28:54.260
or this is fun.

00:28:54.260 --> 00:28:56.020
This is great, but
I'm still exploited.

00:28:56.020 --> 00:28:59.120
The majority of the revenue
still stays with your employer.

00:28:59.120 --> 00:29:01.070
And the big issue
with these systems

00:29:01.070 --> 00:29:04.076
is they're all
implemented in code.

00:29:04.076 --> 00:29:09.510
This is all codified,
algorithmic, automated

00:29:09.510 --> 00:29:10.670
regulation.

00:29:10.670 --> 00:29:13.840
And the big issue with that
is you can't argue with it.

00:29:13.840 --> 00:29:17.690
If you have an
overdraft on your bank,

00:29:17.690 --> 00:29:19.522
you could still go
to your bank teller,

00:29:19.522 --> 00:29:20.980
depending on which
country you are.

00:29:20.980 --> 00:29:22.896
Here, they are typically
very neo autonomized,

00:29:22.896 --> 00:29:24.974
but in European countries, not.

00:29:24.974 --> 00:29:27.390
And then you can say listen,
you've known me for 10 years,

00:29:27.390 --> 00:29:29.265
and I only need an
extension for another day,

00:29:29.265 --> 00:29:31.175
and I'd pay the money
back, and he does so.

00:29:31.175 --> 00:29:32.800
We know there will
always be exceptions

00:29:32.800 --> 00:29:33.660
to the rule in reality.

00:29:33.660 --> 00:29:35.600
The only issues with
these algorithmic system.

00:29:35.600 --> 00:29:36.981
I can't argue with them.

00:29:36.981 --> 00:29:38.480
I don't even know
according to which

00:29:38.480 --> 00:29:40.965
rules they tell me yes or no
or give me certain rewards.

00:29:40.965 --> 00:29:43.104
And I can't change
that, contrary

00:29:43.104 --> 00:29:45.470
to other political systems.

00:29:45.470 --> 00:29:47.069
So basically, the
control fear is

00:29:47.069 --> 00:29:49.235
that it's on the one hand,
big brother watching you,

00:29:49.235 --> 00:29:51.330
because it's constant
surveillance in the back,

00:29:51.330 --> 00:29:54.170
and all your data is captured.

00:29:54.170 --> 00:29:56.030
It comes with the
playfuls of veneers,

00:29:56.030 --> 00:29:58.280
so it's the Aldous Huxley soma.

00:29:58.280 --> 00:30:01.520
All this is fun and happy, and
why should we care about it?

00:30:01.520 --> 00:30:03.950
And it's a little bit
overload, because all of this

00:30:03.950 --> 00:30:04.969
is run by computers.

00:30:04.969 --> 00:30:08.400
It's not even run
by people anymore.

00:30:08.400 --> 00:30:11.690
As I said, this is going to be
the worst case scenario here.

00:30:11.690 --> 00:30:13.980
The big issue obviously,
which I pointed out in text

00:30:13.980 --> 00:30:17.560
here is that these
kind of control systems

00:30:17.560 --> 00:30:20.600
destroy the very thing that
makes games fun to begin with.

00:30:20.600 --> 00:30:23.695
They give you the freedom of
playing, voluntary choosing

00:30:23.695 --> 00:30:24.540
to the activity.

00:30:27.150 --> 00:30:29.196
Second, and third,
and then we're

00:30:29.196 --> 00:30:31.170
done with negative vision.

00:30:31.170 --> 00:30:34.401
The second negative
vision is gamification

00:30:34.401 --> 00:30:36.275
doesn't even lead to
more control in society.

00:30:36.275 --> 00:30:38.940
It just reproduces
existing society as it is.

00:30:38.940 --> 00:30:41.685
It reproduces the
systems and the rhetorics

00:30:41.685 --> 00:30:44.085
that we have in our system.

00:30:44.085 --> 00:30:46.230
The overarching
narrative, if you

00:30:46.230 --> 00:30:50.210
look at persuasive technology
with the quantified self,

00:30:50.210 --> 00:30:50.936
[INAUDIBLE].

00:30:50.936 --> 00:30:54.160
The overarching rhetoric
of all of these systems

00:30:54.160 --> 00:30:57.865
is when we have
social issues or when

00:30:57.865 --> 00:31:00.590
we have individual
issues like obesity,

00:31:00.590 --> 00:31:03.980
like climate change, or
stuff like that, it's

00:31:03.980 --> 00:31:07.390
the individual's fault.
It's the individual's fault,

00:31:07.390 --> 00:31:11.350
because all of these systems
address individual behavior.

00:31:11.350 --> 00:31:13.784
If only I motivated you
to run a bit better,

00:31:13.784 --> 00:31:14.700
you'd not [INAUDIBLE].

00:31:14.700 --> 00:31:17.440
If only I motivated you to drive
a bit more fuel efficiently

00:31:17.440 --> 00:31:20.450
each day, we wouldn't have
global warming, basically.

00:31:20.450 --> 00:31:22.430
That's the argument by
addressing these things

00:31:22.430 --> 00:31:24.990
through specified applications.

00:31:24.990 --> 00:31:27.320
So basically, the
underlying rhetoric there

00:31:27.320 --> 00:31:30.617
is this very American one.

00:31:30.617 --> 00:31:32.700
Anything can be accomplished
if one has the desire

00:31:32.700 --> 00:31:35.310
and determination.

00:31:35.310 --> 00:31:37.810
If there is a social issue, if
there is an individual issue,

00:31:37.810 --> 00:31:40.850
it's because the individual
didn't have the willpower.

00:31:40.850 --> 00:31:42.370
And basically, these
technical tools

00:31:42.370 --> 00:31:44.680
just give you an augmentation
to your willpower

00:31:44.680 --> 00:31:49.124
by motivating you if you
can't motivate yourself.

00:31:49.124 --> 00:31:50.915
Is there anything wrong
with this rhetoric?

00:31:50.915 --> 00:31:51.550
Well, let's see.

00:31:51.550 --> 00:31:53.966
There are other places where
the same rhetoric was around,

00:31:53.966 --> 00:31:56.130
like Maoist China, where
we had slogans like when

00:31:56.130 --> 00:32:00.080
discipline's reinforced,
revolution cannot fail,

00:32:00.080 --> 00:32:04.110
saying if the great leap forward
trying to mass industrialize

00:32:04.110 --> 00:32:08.180
a country of several hundred
million people within the term

00:32:08.180 --> 00:32:11.440
of five years, if that
kills millions of people,

00:32:11.440 --> 00:32:13.984
it's not because the planet
was bonkers to begin with.

00:32:13.984 --> 00:32:18.630
It's because the individuals
didn't put in enough effort.

00:32:18.630 --> 00:32:22.190
In the same way, I think
gamification and lots

00:32:22.190 --> 00:32:24.955
of persuasive technology
makes the same issue

00:32:24.955 --> 00:32:26.870
of the background
systemic root causes.

00:32:26.870 --> 00:32:30.630
The deeper underlying
societal issues

00:32:30.630 --> 00:32:33.706
that are not caused
by individual behavior

00:32:33.706 --> 00:32:35.690
necessarily or that are
not just [INAUDIBLE]

00:32:35.690 --> 00:32:37.560
on the individual weather.

00:32:37.560 --> 00:32:41.810
You'll interpret the [INAUDIBLE]
of environmental psychology

00:32:41.810 --> 00:32:43.560
that recently made the
same argument where

00:32:43.560 --> 00:32:45.450
it said, we're basically
fooling ourselves

00:32:45.450 --> 00:32:48.222
if we believe that getting
people to recycle more

00:32:48.222 --> 00:32:51.230
will solve any of our
environmental issues,

00:32:51.230 --> 00:32:58.120
because municipal loves
production, just as an example.

00:32:58.120 --> 00:33:00.800
So all the waste
that everybody of us

00:33:00.800 --> 00:33:02.620
produces in a city
that's collected

00:33:02.620 --> 00:33:04.950
by the municipalities,
all the waste

00:33:04.950 --> 00:33:07.645
that we produce-- how much
is municipal waste production

00:33:07.645 --> 00:33:10.570
from total US waste production?

00:33:10.570 --> 00:33:12.250
What share?

00:33:12.250 --> 00:33:12.940
Any numbers?

00:33:17.547 --> 00:33:18.520
AUDIENCE: 10%.

00:33:18.520 --> 00:33:20.770
SEBASTIAN DETERDING:
10%, more or less.

00:33:20.770 --> 00:33:21.312
AUDIENCE: 5%.

00:33:21.312 --> 00:33:22.894
SEBASTIAN DETERDING:
5%, more or less.

00:33:22.894 --> 00:33:23.650
AUDIENCE: 2%?

00:33:23.650 --> 00:33:27.480
SEBASTIAN DETERDING:
2%-- too low-- 3%.

00:33:27.480 --> 00:33:32.060
So if you all recycle more,
we're reducing 10% of 3%,

00:33:32.060 --> 00:33:34.855
whereas most of the
waste productions

00:33:34.855 --> 00:33:36.230
happens in industrial
production.

00:33:36.230 --> 00:33:38.920
Most of the waste production
happens in supply chains.

00:33:38.920 --> 00:33:41.120
It doesn't happen at the
level of individual waste.

00:33:41.120 --> 00:33:42.880
Same goes for energy savings.

00:33:42.880 --> 00:33:44.516
Same goes for all the issues.

00:33:44.516 --> 00:33:48.410
We're addressing the wrong
things with this kind of thing

00:33:48.410 --> 00:33:52.010
if we're always focusing
on the individual behavior.

00:33:52.010 --> 00:33:55.320
Third and final one
is it's not control.

00:33:55.320 --> 00:33:57.640
It's not even reproducing
existing social order.

00:33:57.640 --> 00:34:00.510
It's just reference.

00:34:00.510 --> 00:34:04.046
My favorite example for
that is the PlayPump,

00:34:04.046 --> 00:34:07.260
a system invented by a civil
engineer in South Africa

00:34:07.260 --> 00:34:08.960
sometime in the 90s.

00:34:08.960 --> 00:34:12.764
And in 1994, a retired
advertising executive

00:34:12.764 --> 00:34:14.639
discovered it and said,
this is a great idea.

00:34:14.639 --> 00:34:17.290
Let me buy the patent,
and let me make this big.

00:34:17.290 --> 00:34:20.460
The idea of the
PlayPump is basically

00:34:20.460 --> 00:34:22.800
lots of cities in Africa
and other developing nations

00:34:22.800 --> 00:34:25.449
don't have enough
fresh water pumps.

00:34:25.449 --> 00:34:27.010
So what they said
is hey, instead

00:34:27.010 --> 00:34:28.790
of the traditional
fresh water pumps,

00:34:28.790 --> 00:34:33.239
let's install a fresh water pump
that's actually a roundabout

00:34:33.239 --> 00:34:36.880
and put a reservoir on top of
it that's seen here, behind.

00:34:36.880 --> 00:34:43.960
And so water is pumped for
the local village's water

00:34:43.960 --> 00:34:45.614
consumption by the
children playing.

00:34:45.614 --> 00:34:46.989
Nobody has to work
for the water.

00:34:46.989 --> 00:34:48.655
The children enjoy
using the roundabout.

00:34:48.655 --> 00:34:50.034
They will pump the water up.

00:34:50.034 --> 00:34:51.909
And you know how we pay
for this whole thing?

00:34:51.909 --> 00:34:54.639
We use the reservoir as
an advertising space.

00:34:54.639 --> 00:34:58.310
So the advertisers will pay
for the installment of this.

00:34:58.310 --> 00:34:59.410
It's a great story.

00:34:59.410 --> 00:35:01.160
It's a great new
story to say hey,

00:35:01.160 --> 00:35:04.360
water is easy as child's
play, dah, dah, dah, dah, dah.

00:35:04.360 --> 00:35:06.345
It got a great, favorable
PBS documentary,

00:35:06.345 --> 00:35:09.640
lots of other favorable
press attention.

00:35:09.640 --> 00:35:11.890
He got then $60
million US dollars

00:35:11.890 --> 00:35:15.201
in aid promised from US aid.

00:35:15.201 --> 00:35:17.100
Only then, development
aid workers

00:35:17.100 --> 00:35:19.945
started raising their
hands and saying, sorry.

00:35:19.945 --> 00:35:22.236
Nobody wants to advertise it
to the developing nations,

00:35:22.236 --> 00:35:27.880
it turns out, especially
not in rural villages.

00:35:27.880 --> 00:35:32.780
And they found out that the pump
is more difficult to install,

00:35:32.780 --> 00:35:37.280
less efficient, more difficult
to service than existing water

00:35:37.280 --> 00:35:39.270
pumps in other cultures.

00:35:39.270 --> 00:35:41.740
And they found that the
average water consumption

00:35:41.740 --> 00:35:45.350
of an average African
village is so big

00:35:45.350 --> 00:35:46.880
that children would
have to operate

00:35:46.880 --> 00:35:48.379
the roundabout with
their body power

00:35:48.379 --> 00:35:51.556
for 27 continuous hours per day.

00:35:51.556 --> 00:35:52.930
So it's impossible.

00:35:52.930 --> 00:35:55.140
It's impossible that
children can produce

00:35:55.140 --> 00:35:57.780
enough water [INAUDIBLE].

00:35:57.780 --> 00:36:01.882
So therefore, it ended up
that the adults were operating

00:36:01.882 --> 00:36:03.340
the roundabout,
only the roundabout

00:36:03.340 --> 00:36:04.340
was built for children.

00:36:04.340 --> 00:36:06.760
So the adults always had to
hunker down and use this one,

00:36:06.760 --> 00:36:09.110
so they were breaking their
backs as they were doing so,

00:36:09.110 --> 00:36:11.910
very literally.

00:36:11.910 --> 00:36:15.890
So this thing is
a great new story

00:36:15.890 --> 00:36:19.110
that gives you great pictures
with all kinds of things.

00:36:19.110 --> 00:36:22.290
And the argument, or the
fear, or the negative vision

00:36:22.290 --> 00:36:24.260
here is that gamification,
like the PlayPump,

